alternatives.transcript: good afternoon doctor rollins i saw miss leslie today she is a sixty two year old woman who presents to the office for a chief complaint of shortness of breath fatigue heart flutter and palpitations miss leslie was in her usual state of excellent excellent health until two months ago when she developed worsening shortness of breath and palpitations she reports the symptoms being better at rest and when she's elevated and worse during physical activity she does feel like passing out at times she does not complain of radiating pain miss leslie does have a history of sarcoidosis which she was diagnosed twenty five years ago and is currently being treated for hypertension with lisinopril along with the along with lisinopril she reports taking prednisone as well she has no known allergies her social history includes a balanced diet limited exercise no drug use no tobacco use no alcohol use and moderate caffeine use she is an elementary school teacher she is sexually active and in a relationship her past surgical history includes a cardiac cath about one year ago and she has no prior hospitalizations her father died of a heart attack at fifty nine and her mother had a sudden death at forty she appears awake alert oriented fatigued and presents with weight gain of about eight pounds and swollen ankles review of systems of her skin was negative review of systems of her musculoskeletal component was negative and her blood pressure was elevated at one thirty six over ninety nine and her heart rate was also elevated at one ten upon palpitation edema was noted in her ankles lower extremity pulses were normal bilaterally she did present with rales bilaterally and wheezing she was active she was negative for coleman's test and had no tart or spinal abnormalities during her osteopathic screening her chest x-ray showed normal cardiac silhouette mediastinal fullness and pulmonary edema her bnp was elevated at four thousand troponin was still on normal levels her ekg demonstrated normal sinus rhythm with a nonsustained left ventricular tachycardia her t two d echo showed increased wall thickness with an ejection fraction of fifty percent and she was up to date with her immunizations she was diagnosed with sarcoidosis restrictive cardiomyopathy and was admitted to telometry in terms of medication amiodarone one fifty mg and furosemide forty mg iv was added and prednisone was increased to sixty mg from ten mg she will be on a low sodium diet and will be receiving out of bed assistance cmp was ordered and an interventional cardiology consult for aic for aicd placement nuclear med consult for fdg pet was indicated she will be continuing her lisinopril medication
